words.etymology_text: Internationalism (compare English Swabia), ultimately from Latin Suābia. Equivalent to svaabi + -ia.

forms.form: Rare. Only used with substantive adjectives.

words.etymology_text: Calque of German Schweitzerpfeiff (“fife”); Sveitsin (“Swiss”) + huilu (“flute”).

glosses: Swissness (state or quality of being Swiss)
Swiss schnitzel (dish consisting of veal cutlet filled with cheese, typically Emmentaler or Gruyere, and a slice of ham)
Swiss hound, Schweizer Laufhund (Swiss breed of dog)

raw_glosses: (historical) Swiss Guard (mercenary guard consisting of Swiss soldiers seeking their fortune abroad due to the poverty of their home country)
glosses: Swiss Guard (mercenary guard consisting of Swiss soldiers seeking their fortune abroad due to the poverty of their home country)
Swiss Guard (pontifical Swiss Guard stationed in Vatican, the only remaining unit of this kind)

forms.form: Rare. Only used with substantive adjectives.

words.etymology_text: Formed according to other similar terms, such as fennomaani (“Fennoman”), gallomaani (“Gallomaniac”); cognate with Swedish svekoman.

words.etymology_text: Borrowed from Swedish svänga. Compare also English swing.

glosses: An expression influenced by Swedish, often one that is regarded as non-standard in the target language, particularly in Finnish.

words.etymology_text: From Latin Suecia (“Sweden”) + -ismi, by analogy with terms such as anglismi and latinismi.
